The '''Arrow''' or '''''Hetz''''' ({{lang-he|<U+05D7><U+05E5>}}, {{IPA-he|x<U+025B>ts|pron}}) is a family of [[anti-ballistic missile]]s designed to fulfill an Israeli requirement for a [[missile defense|theater missile defense system]] that would be more effective against [[ballistic missile]]s than the [[MIM-104 Patriot]] [[surface-to-air missile]]. Jointly funded and produced by [[Israel]] and the [[United States]], development of the system began in 1986 and has continued since,<ref name=global/> drawing some contested criticism.<ref name="inss" /> Undertaken by [[Israel Aerospace Industries]] (IAI) and [[Boeing]], it is overseen by the [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Israeli Ministry of Defence's]] "''Homa''" ({{lang-he|<U+05D7><U+05D5><U+05DE><U+05D4>}}, {{IPA-he|xoma|pron}}, "[[Defensive wall|rampart]]") missile defense agency and the U.S. [[Missile Defense Agency]]. 

The Arrow system consists of the joint production [[hypersonic]] Arrow anti-missile interceptor, [[Elta]] EL/M-2080 '''"Green Pine"''' [[Early warning radar|early-warning]] [[Active Electronically Scanned Array|AESA]] [[radar]],<ref name="elta">{{cite web |publisher =[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |accessdate=2009-08-19 |url= http://www.iai.co.il/17660-27136-en/default.aspx Elta |title= EL/M-2080 "Green Pine" Radar System}}</ref> the [[Tadiran Telecom]] '''"Golden Citron"''' ("Citron Tree") [[C4ISTAR|C<sup>3</sup>I]] center,<ref name="tadiran"/> and the [[Israel Aerospace Industries]] '''"Brown Hazelnut"''' ("Hazelnut Tree") launch control center. The system is transportable rather than mobile, as it can be moved to other prepared sites but cannot be set up just anywhere.<ref name="Egozi2"/>

Following construction and testing of the Arrow 1 technology demonstrator,<ref name=iafs/> production and deployment began with the Arrow 2 version of the missile. The Arrow is considered one of the most advanced missile defense programs currently in existence.<ref name=mstrt>{{cite web |url= http://missilethreat.com/missiledefensesystems/id.10/system_detail.asp |publisher=[[Claremont Institute]] MissileThreat.com |title=Missile Defense Systems: Arrow |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref name="jewish">{{cite web |url=http://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/US-Israel/Arrow.html |publisher=[[Jewish Virtual Library]] |title= The Arrow Missile Program |accessdate=2009-08-21}}</ref> It is the first operational missile defense system specifically designed and built to intercept and destroy ballistic missiles.<ref name=nti>{{cite web |url=http://www.nti.org/e_research/profiles/Israel/Missile/index.html |publisher=[[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] |title=Israel profile: Missile overview: Arrow Anti-ballistic Missile Defense System |date=2008-10 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref name=aipac>{{cite web |url=http://www.aipac.org/Publications/AIPACAnalysesIssueBriefs/U.S.-Israel_Missile_Defense_Cooperation.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[American Israel Public Affairs Committee]] |title=U.S.-Israel Missile Defense Cooperation |date=2001-12-06 |accessdate=2009-08-21}}</ref> Arrow 3 is expected in the near future.<ref name=dua3/> The first Arrow battery was declared fully operational in October 2000.<ref name=tests/> Although several of its components have been exported, the [[Israeli Air Defense Network]] within the [[Israeli Air Force]] (IAF) of the [[Israel Defense Forces]] (IDF) is currently the sole user of the complete Arrow system.

==Background==
{{seealso|Arab<U+2013>Israeli conflict}}
The Arrow program was launched in light of the acquisition by [[Arab League|Arab states]] of long ranged [[surface-to-surface missile]]s.<ref name="iafs" /><ref name=dtic /> The United States and Israel signed a [[memorandum of understanding]] to co-fund it on May 6, 1986,<ref name="global" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.policyalmanac.org/world/archive/crs_israeli-us_relations.shtml |author=Clyde R. Mark |publisher=Almanac of Policy Issues |title=Israeli-United States Relations |date=2002-10-17 | accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> and in 1988 the [[United States Department of Defense]] [[Strategic Defense Initiative|Strategic Defense Initiative Organization]] (SDIO) placed an order with Israel Aircraft Industries for the Arrow 1 technology demonstrator.<ref name="armytec">{{cite web | publisher = army-technology.com | title = Arrow 2 Theatre Ballistic Missile Defence System, Israel | url = http://www.army-technology.com/projects/arrow2/ | accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref group=n>Over the years SDIO was renamed to [[Ballistic Missile Defense Organization]] (BMDO), and later to [[Missile Defense Agency]] (MDA), while Israel Aircraft Industries was renamed to [[Israel Aerospace Industries]].</ref> The [[Gulf War]], which exposed the controversial performance<ref name="fas_patriot">{{citation | url = http://www.fas.org/spp/starwars/congress/1992_h/ | title =The performance of the Patriot missile in the Gulf| |author1-link=Theodore Postol |first1= Theodore |last1= Postol | first2= Reuven |last2= Pedatzur | first3= Charles |last3= Zraket |author4-link=Peter Zimmerman |first4= Peter |last4= Zimmerman | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]]| date = 1992-04-07}}. Retrieved 2009-10-09.</ref> of the [[MIM-104 Patriot|Patriot missile]] against [[Iraq]]i "[[Al Hussein (missile)|Al Hussein]]" missiles, gave further impetus to the development of the Arrow.<ref name="iafs" /> It was initially designed to intercept missiles such as "Al Hussein", its original - [[Scud|SS-1 "Scud"]], [[Soviet Union|USSR]]-made [[OTR-21 Tochka|SS-21 "Scarab"]] of [[Syria]], and [[People's Republic of China|China]]-made [[Dongfeng (missile)#Dongfeng 3 (CSS-2)|CSS-2]] of [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=dtic /> [[Yitzhak Rabin]], then [[Prime Minister of Israel]] and [[Defense Minister of Israel]], viewed the emerging missile threat as one of the most dangerous future threats on Israel's security.<ref name="inss" /> He said of the program that:
{{cquote|I had the honor, during my term of office as Minister of Defense, in the [[National Unity Government#Israel|National Unity Government]], to vote in favor of Israel's participation in the Strategic Defense Initiative... introduced by [[Ronald Reagan|President Reagan]]...<ref name="tests" />}}
The Israeli [[Administration for the Development of Weapons and the Technological Industry]], part of the [[Ministry of Defense (Israel)|Israeli Ministry of Defense]], runs the Arrow development project under the ''"Homa"'' missile defense agency which binds together Israel's different defense industries. It is also commonly referred to as the IMDO - Israel Missile Defense Organization.

===Funding===
{{seealso|Israel <U+2013> United States military relations}}
The multi-billion dollar development program of the Arrow is undertaken in Israel with the financial support of the United States. When the development program began, the projection for the total cost of its development and manufacture <U+2014> including the initial production of missiles <U+2014> was an estimated $1.6 billion.<ref name="haalong" /> The price of a single Arrow missile was estimated at $3 million.<ref name="haalong" /> Between 1989 and 2007 some $2.4 billion had been reportedly invested in the Arrow program, 50%<U+2013>80%<ref name="a3-80">{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/newscast/0808/0709_arrow-3.html |publisher=[http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] |title=Israel Asks U.S. to Support Arrow-3 | accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> of which was funded by the [[federal government of the United States]].<ref name="defup">{{cite web | title = Israel's Strategic Defense Programs: Missile defense System's Update | publisher = [http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] | date = 2007-03-01 | accessdate=2009-08-19 | url = http://www.defense-update.com/features/du-2-06/feature-ILmissiledefense.htm}}</ref> Israel contributes approximately $65 million annually.<ref name="haalong">{{cite web | title = An Arrow to the heart | publisher = [[Haaretz]] | author=Amnon Barzilai | accessdate=2009-09-18 | url = http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/pages/ShArt.jhtml?itemNo=230843&contrassID=2&subContrassID=1&sbSubContrassID=0&listSrc=Y}}</ref>

