===Criticism===
A criticism of the concept of missile defense for Israel was aired by Dr. [[Reuven Pedatzur]] in a comprehensive study<ref name="peda">{{Cite book |ISBN=9654590050 |publisher= Jaffee Center for Strategic Studies |place=[[Tel Aviv University]] |title=The Arrow Project and Active Defense - Challenges and Questions |id=Paper #42 |first=Reuven |last=Pedatzur |date=1993-10 |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref> published in 1993 by the Jaffe Center for Strategic Studies<ref group=n>Forerunner of the [[Institute for National Security Studies]] (INSS).</ref> The arguments made in the study conformed to the opinions of numerous defense officials and analysts, and echoed many of the arguments made by the [[Strategic Defense Initiative]] critics in the United States.<ref name="inss">{{cite web |url=http://www.inss.org.il/upload/%28FILE%291216205936.pdf |format=PDF | pages = 67-69, 75-77 |publisher=[[Institute for National Security Studies]] |title=Missile Defense and Israel's Deterrence against a Nuclear Iran |author=Dr. [[Uzi Rubin]] |date=2008 |accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref> 

Pedatzur argued that it was exceedingly simple to fool an Arrow-type defensive system with simple, cheap, and easily installed countermeasures, which would render the Arrow system ineffective. He doubted Israel's defense industries could rise to the challenge of such a complex system, citing anonymous experts in the IDF who predicted that the system would not be available before 2010. He envisaged enormous costs, some $10 billion,<ref name="haalong" /> that would distort budgeting priorities and divert funds from the vital enhancement of the IDF's warfighting capability, thus forcing a profound revision of Israel's national security doctrine. He further argued that even if effective against missiles with [[conventional warfare|conventional]], [[Chemical warfare|chemical]] or [[Biological warfare|biological]] [[warhead]]s, the Arrow would not be relevant against future threats of missiles with [[Nuclear weapon|nuclear]] warheads, since it would never be able to supply hermetic defense and the impact of even a single nuclear warhead in Israel's [[Population density|densely populated]] [[urban area]] would be an existential threat to Israel.<ref name="inss" /><ref name=dtic />

At the same time, [[John E. Pike]], who worked then with the [[Federation of American Scientists]], stated that "given technical problems with the systems radar and command system, coupled with its high development cost, the Arrow program may soon fall by the wayside".<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Pike  | first1 = John | author1-link = John E. Pike | last2 = Bolkcom | first2 = Christopher | title = 3. Air Defense Effectiveness | journal = [http://www.fas.org/spp/aircraft/ Attack Aircraft. Proliferation: Issues for Concern] | publisher = [[Federation of American Scientists]] | date = 1993-04-01 - 1996-06-15 | url = http://www.fas.org/spp/aircraft/part03.htm |accessdate=2009-09-20}}</ref>

According to Dr. [[Uzi Rubin]], first Director of IMDO, with the passage of time most of the pessimistic predictions have proven to be unfounded. Israel's defense industries overcame the technical challenge, the system's development was completed a full decade ahead of what was predicted, and there are no indications that the expenditures for the Arrow harmed other IDF procurement plans to any degree whatsoever.<ref name="inss" /> Rubin insists that Israel's missile defense is now an established fact and that most of the warnings issued by critics have failed to materialize.<ref name="inss" /> Pedatzur, however, remains unconvinced.<ref name="peda3" /><ref name="peda2">{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1065134.html |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |title=It's possible to live with Iran |author=Dr. [[Reuven Pedatzur]] |date=2009-02-18 |accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref>

==Development==
[[File:Arrow Missile Model II.JPG|thumb|upright|right|alt=A mockup of the Arrow 1, at the Technion <U+2013> Israel Institute of Technology. |A [[mockup]] of the Arrow 1, at the [[Technion <U+2013> Israel Institute of Technology]].]]
===Arrow 1===
The first launch of the Arrow interceptor took place on August 9, 1990, designed to test the missile's control and guidance systems. The test came to a halt seconds after take off and the missile was intentionally destroyed due to fears it might go off track and hit a settled location. This was caused by the failure of the ground tracking radars to track the missile's [[trajectory]].<ref name=iaft>{{cite web | publisher = [[Israeli Air Force]] | title= Israel Aircraft Industries 'Arrow' ('Hetz') - In action | url = http://www.iaf.org.il/Templates/Aircraft/Aircraft.IN.aspx?lang=EN&lobbyID=69&folderID=87&docfolderID=907&docID=18137&currentPageNumber=6 | accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> Test number two took place on March 25, 1991. Designed to check missile components during launch, it was conducted from a ship at sea. Once again a missile malfunction resulted in the abortion of the experiment.<ref name=iaft/> A third test, designed to examine the Arrow's interception capabilities, was conducted on October 31, 1991. The missile was once again launched from a ship at sea, and was once more aborted because of a repeat of previous malfunctions.<ref name=iaft/>

On September 23, 1992, in another test of the missile components during launch, the systems finally operated as planned and the Arrow reached its designated point in the sky, 45 seconds after launch. As planned, the missile was then destroyed. This successful experiment ended the system's preliminary testing phase.<ref name=iaft/> The fifth, sixth, and seventh tests took place on February 28, July 14, and October 14, 1993 respectively. During these, the Arrow managed to pass in close proximity to the target missiles, thereby proving its ability to intercept surface-to-surface missiles.<ref name=iaft/> During test number eight on March 1, 1994, the missile was not launched due to a ground computer failure.<ref name=iaft/> The ninth test launch on June 12, 1994, also known as ATD#1 (Arrow Demonstration Test 1), saw an Arrow 1 successfully intercept a target missile launched from a ship anchored in the middle of the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]].<ref name=tests>{{cite web | publisher = [http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] | title= Story of the Arrow Weapon System | url = http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/bg.htm | accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref name=iaft/> 

The Arrow 1 was a two stage [[solid propellant]] missile, with an overall length of {{m to ft|7.5|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=1|wiki=no}}, a body diameter of {{mm to in|1200|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=1|wiki=no}}, and a launch weight of around {{kg to lb|2000|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-2|wiki=no}}. It was estimated that the second stage had a length of {{m to ft|2.5|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=1|wiki=no}}, and that it had [[Inertial navigation system|inertial]] and [[Missile_guidance#Command Off Line-Of-Sight (COLOS)|command update mid-course]] guidance, with a terminal [[Infrared homing|infrared]] [[focal plane]] array. The missile was described as being relatively high-speed and maneuverable, with [[thrust vectoring]] in the both stages. The range capability has been described as around {{km to mi|50|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}}.<ref name=nti2>{{cite web |url=http://nuclearthreatinitiative.org/e_research/profiles/Israel/Missile/3571_5219.html |publisher=[[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] |title=Israel profile: Missile overview: Missile Chronology: 1990-1999 |date=2005-10 |accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref> On the other hand, the Arrow 1 could be a single stage missile.<ref name="stav" /> Development of the "big and cumbersome"<ref name="uzi" /> Arrow 1 then ceased and further research continued with the "smaller, faster and more lethal" Arrow 2.<ref name=iafs/><ref name=tests/>

===Arrow 2===
[[File:Arrow2 96feb.jpg|thumb|alt=Arrow 2 launch in February 1996.|Arrow 2 launch in February 1996.]]
Two successful tests (designated IIT#21 and IIT#22) of the steering, control and cruising systems were conducted without target missiles on July 30, 1995 and February 20, 1996.<ref name=tests/><ref name=iaft/> Two successful interceptions took place on August 20, 1996 and March 11, 1997, and were designated AIT#21 and AIT#22.<ref name=tests/><ref name=iaft/>
[[File:Arrow2 96aug.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|left|alt=Arrow 2 launch in August 1996.|Arrow 2 launch in August 1996.]]
Another interception test (AIT#23) was conducted on August 20, 1997, but the missile was destroyed when the its steering system malfunctioned.<ref name="tests" /><ref name="iaft" /> The fault was corrected in time to ensure the success of AST#3,<ref name=tests/><ref name=iaft/> the first comprehensive test of the entire system. On September 14, 1998, all system components successfully countered a computer-simulated threat.<ref name=tests/><ref name=iaft/> On November 29, 1998, Israel Aerospace Industries delivered the first operational Arrow 2 interceptor to the Israeli Ministry of Defense.<ref name="tests" />

A full system interception test (AST#4) was held on November 1, 1999. During this test the Arrow system located, tracked and intercepted a TM-91C target missile simulating a "Scud" missile, launched on a very steep trajectory from a ship located offshore.<ref name=tests/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/at.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=Arrow System Test No. 4| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> The IAI TM-91C target missile was itself based on the Arrow 1 interceptor.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/tm91c.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=TM-91C Target Missile| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> On March 14, 2000, the first complete Arrow 2 battery was rolled out in a ceremony at [[Palmachim Airbase]].<ref name=tests/> In his speech, then IAF commander [[Aluf]] [[Eitan Ben Eliyahu]] said:
{{cquote|This is a great day for the Air Defense Forces, for the Air Force, the defense establishment and, I would say, for the State of Israel. As of today, we have completed the acceptance of the only weapon system of its kind in the entire world. We are the first-to succeed in developing, building and operating a defense system against ballistic missiles.<ref name="tests"/>}}

Another Arrow 2 test (AST#5) took place on September 14, 2000, this time with a new target missile, the [[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems]] "Black Sparrow".<ref name="rafspar" /> This airborne ballistic target missile, launched by an IAF [[F-15 Eagle|F-15]] towards Israel's coastline at a ballistic trajectory simulating an aggressor "Scud", was intercepted and destroyed.<ref name="iaft" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/test05.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=Arrow System Test No. 5| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> Consequently, the following month saw the Palmachim Arrow battery declared operational by the Israeli Air Defense Network.<ref name=tests/> The "Black Sparrow" has since been used as the aggressor target in the AST#6, AST#9, and AST#10 tests.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/blackSp.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title="Black Sparrow" Target Missile| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> On August 27, 2001 (AST#6), the Arrow system successfully intercepted its target at some {{km to mi|100|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} from shore, the highest and farthest that the Arrow 2 had been tested to date.<ref name=global>{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/space/systems/arrow.htm |author = [[John E. Pike]] |publisher=[[GlobalSecurity.org]] |title=Arrow Theater Missile Defense |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref name=iaft/> In October 2002 the second battery was declared operational.<ref name=tests/>

====Block-2====
[[File:Arrow missile trinity.jpg|right|thumb|upright=2|alt=Arrow 2 launch on August 26, 2004, during AST USFT#2. |Arrow 2 launch on August 26, 2004, during AST USFT#2.]]
A successful test of the Arrow 2 block-2 took place on January 5, 2003 (AST#8). Four missiles were launched towards four simulated targets in order to examine the interceptor's performance during special flight conditions as well as system performance during a sequence of launches.<ref name=iaft/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bdkair-iai.com/28973-23065-en/default.aspx?PageNum=7 |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |title=Successful Arrow Test | date=2003-01-05| accessdate=2009-08-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/test08.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=Arrow System Test No. 8| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> The test did not include actual interceptions.<ref name=iaft/> Another successful test held on December 16, 2003 (AST#9), examined the system's ability to intercept and destroy incoming missiles at significantly high altitudes,<ref name=tests/> around {{km to mi|60|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}}.<ref name=mstrt/> Reportedly, AST#8 and AST#9 also tested integration of the Arrow with Patriot batteries.<ref name=tests/><ref name=iaft/>

On July 29, 2004, Israel and the United States carried out a joint test at the [[Naval Air Station Point Mugu]] (NAS [[Point Mugu]]) Missile Test Center in [[California]], in which the Arrow interceptor was launched against a real "Scud-B" missile. The test represented a realistic scenario that could not have been tested in Israel due to test-field safety restrictions.<ref name=global /> To enable the test a full battery was shipped to Point Mugu. The "Green Pine" radar and [[Command and control (military)|command-and-control]] systems were deployed at the base, while the Arrow launcher was installed {{km to mi|100|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} offshore on an island that forms part of the test range.<ref name="Egozi">{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2004/08/03/185346/arrow-destroys-scud-b-target-in-us-ballistic-missile-test.html |publisher=[[Flightglobal.com]] |title=Arrow destroys Scud-B target in US ballistic-missile test |author=Arie Egozi |date=2004-08-03 |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref> The test was a success, with the interceptor destroying the "Scud" that flew a {{km to mi|300|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} trajectory<ref name="Egozi" /> at an altitude of {{km to mi|40|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}},<ref name=armytec/> west of [[San Nicolas Island]].<ref name="mdalink">{{cite web |url=http://www.mda.mil/mdalink/html/arrthum.html#arrow.ANC |publisher=[[Missile Defense Agency]] |title=Program Images: Arrow |accessdate=2009-09-01}}</ref> This was the twelfth Arrow interceptor test and the seventh test of the complete system, the first interception of a real "Scud".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/testUS1.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=Arrow System Test USFT#1| accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> This significant test became known as the AST USFT#1.<ref name="tests" /> Following this test, then [[Defense Minister of Israel]], [[Shaul Mofaz]], said:
{{cquote|We are in an age of uncertainty. Countries in the 'third circle' [Iran] are continuing their efforts to acquire non-conventional capabilities along with long-range launch capabilities. The Arrow is the best missile system of its kind in the world, and represents a force multiplier for our future force.<ref name="ido">{{cite web |url=http://www.isracast.com/article.aspx?id=100 |title=The Arrow Missile scores a direct hit| publisher=isracast.com |date=2004-08-10 |accessdate=2009-08-19 |author=Iddo Genuth}}</ref>}}

AST USFT#2 was conducted at NAS Point Mugu a month later, on August 26. This test was aimed at examining the Arrow's ability to detect a splitting warhead of a separating ballistic missile.<ref name="armytec" /> It detected the true target, but a technical malfunction reportedly prevented it from maneuvering to strike it,<ref name="passes">{{cite web |url=http://www.jinsa.org/node/565 |publisher=[[Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs]] |title=Arrow Passes Toughest Test Yet |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> leading to a suspension of testing.<ref name="armytec" /> Testing was resumed in December 2005, when the system successfully intercepted a target at an unspecified but reported record low altitude.<ref name=armytec/> This test (AST#10) was the fourteenth test of the Arrow missile and the ninth test of the complete system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/test10.htm |publisher=[http://www.mod.gov.il/pages/homa/index.htm Israel Missile Defense Organization] |title=Arrow System Test No. 10|accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref>

====Block-3====
[[File:Arrow Missile Exhibition II.jpg|thumb|alt=Arrow 2 on display at Rishon LeZion in September 2008. |Arrow 2 on display at [[Rishon LeZion]] in September 2008]]
In February 11, 2007 an Arrow 2 block-3<ref name=sipri>{{cite book| author=[[Stockholm International Peace Research Institute]]| title =SIPRI Yearbook 2008: Armaments, Disarmament, and International Security | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]]| year = 2008 |page= 413 | isbn = 9780199548958 |url = http://books.google.com/books?id=EAyQ9KCJE2gC |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref> successfully intercepted and destroyed a "Black Sparrow" target missile simulating a ballistic missile at high altitude.<ref name=armytec/> It was the first so-called distributed weapon system test conducted in Israel, which required two Arrow units deployed some {{km to mi|100|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} apart to share data on incoming threats and coordinate launching assignments. It was also the first time the [[Link 16]] data distribution system was used to connect two Arrow units, although the system had been used in previous tests to connect Arrow and Patriot batteries.<ref name="passes"/> Furthermore, an improved launcher was used.<ref name="mda2" /> 

A precursor of the next block was launched without a target on March 26, 2007 in order to gather information on its flight and performance,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/842111.html |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |author=Amos Harel |title=Anti-missile exercise tests electronics of Arrow system |date=2007-03-26 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> introducing unspecified modifications to its [[hardware]] and [[electronics]] and reduced manufacturing costs by some 20%.<ref name="blk4">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1173879176877&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=IAF launches new 'cheap' Arrow |author=Yaakov Katz |date=2007-03-26 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref> [[Arieh Herzog]], Director of IMDO, has said: "Our Arrow operational system can without a doubt deal with all of the operational threats in the Middle East, particularly in Iran and Syria."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1173879211495&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |author=Yaakov Katz |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=Arrow can fully protect against Iran |date=2007-03-30 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref>

====Block-4====
On April 15, 2008 the Arrow weapon system successfully detected and made a simulated intercept of a new target missile,<ref name=armytec/> the "Blue Sparrow", a successor of the "Black Sparrow" capable of simulating "Scud-C/D" missiles<ref name="rafspar">{{cite web |url=http://www.rafael.co.il/marketing/SIP_STORAGE/FILES/2/622.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems]] |title=Sparrow targets brochure |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> and reportedly the [[Iran]]ian [[Shahab-3]] as well.<ref name=armytec/> During the test, a target missile was launched from an IAF F-15 at a height of 90,000 feet (27.5&nbsp;km). The missile split into [[Multiple independently targetable reentry vehicle|multiple warheads]], making it harder to intercept it. Nevertheless, the Arrow's radar tracked the missile, simulating an intercept.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/975269.html |author=Amos Harel |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |title=Arrow successfully simulates intercept of mock Shihab missile |date=2008-04-15 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref> In September 2008 the IDF attempted a test of actual Arrow 2 block-4 missile against the "Blue Sparrow". The drill had to be aborted, however, when the target missile malfunctioned shortly after launch.<ref name=fox>{{cite web |url=http://www.foxnews.com/story/0,2933,512970,00.html |publisher=[[Fox News]] |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=Israel Successfully Tests Anti-Missile System to Protect Against Iran |date=2009-04-07 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> Eventually the Arrow 2 block-4 was successfully tested against the "Blue Sparrow" on April 7, 2009.<ref name=fox/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iai.co.il/32981-39454-en/default.aspx |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |title=Improved Arrow Missile Destroys Target in Latest Test of the System |date=2009-04-07 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1238562933063&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |author=Yaakov Katz |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=Israel successfully tests Arrow 2 defense system |date=2009-04-07 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> The test also witnessed the first integration of the Arrow with the U.S. [[AN/TPY-2]] [[X band]] radar deployed at [[Dimona Radar Facility]].<ref name=dua3>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/products/a/arrow3.html |publisher=[http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] |title=Israel, U.S. to Embark on Collaborative 'Upper-Tier' Missile Intercept Program to include Arrow 3 and Land-Based SM-3 Missiles |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref>

A July 22, 2009, joint test of the Arrow 2 block-4 against an airborne target missile with a range of over {{km to mi|1000|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} once again at the NAS Point Mugu,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSN14292699 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |author=David Morgan |title=Israel to test Arrow missile on U.S. Pacific range |accessdate=2009-08-19 |date=2009-07-14}}</ref> was reportedly aborted after the missile failed to establish a communications link.<ref name="last">{{cite web |url=http://www.defense-update.com/newscast/0709/news/arrow_2_test_230709.html |publisher=[http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] |title=Arrow-II Aborts Long-Range Intercept Test |date=2009-07-23 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> A target had been released from a [[C-17 Globemaster III]] aircraft,<ref name="mdaa" /><ref name="mda" /> the radar detected the target and transferred its tracks,<ref name="last" /> but the interceptor was not launched.<ref name="mdaa">{{cite web |url = http://missiledefense.wordpress.com/2009/07/23/arrow-missile-defense-fails-test/ |publisher=[[Missile Defense Advocacy Alliance]] |title=Arrow missile defense fails test |date=2009-07-23 |accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref> The aborted test was widely referred to as a failure,<ref name="mdaa" /><ref name="peda3">{{cite web |url = http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1103395.html |publisher=[[Haaretz]] |title=Even if the Hetz succeeds |author=Dr. [[Reuven Pedatzur]] |accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref> however objectives of interoperability with other ballistic missile defense systems were achieved.<ref name="mda">{{cite web |url=http://www.mda.mil/mdalink/pdf/09news0014.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Missile Defense Agency]] |title=News release: July 22, 2009|date=2009-07-22 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> The test continued under a simulative mode, with by the [[Aegis Combat System|Aegis]] [[Arleigh Burke class destroyer|destroyer]], [[USS Benfold (DDG-65)]] which also participated in the test.<ref name="last" /><ref name="mda" />

===Arrow 3===
{{external media|align = right|width = 190px |image2 = [http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/he/5/50/Arrow_3_KV.jpg Computer-generated image of Arrow 3 kill vehicle in space]|image1 = [http://defense-update.com/Images_new3/Arrow-3_Exo-Atmospheric.jpg Arrow 3 kill vehicle on display at the 2009 Paris Air Show]}}
By August 2008 the United States and Israeli governments have initiated development of an upper-tier component to the Israeli Air Defense Network, known as Arrow 3, "with a kill ratio of around 99 percent".<ref name=nti3>{{cite web |url=http://nuclearthreatinitiative.org/e_research/profiles/Israel/Missile/3571_6330.html |publisher=[[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] |title=Israel profile: Missile overview: Missile Chronology: 2007-2009 |date=2009-02 |accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref> The development is based on an architecture definition study conducted in 2006-2007, determining the need for the upper-tier component to be integrated into Israel's ballistic missile defense system. According to Arieh Herzog, the main element of this upper tier will be an exoatmospheric interceptor, to be jointly developed by IAI and [[Boeing]].<ref name=dua3/> [[Lieutenant General]] [[Patrick J. O<U+2019>Reilly]], Director of the Missile Defense Agency, said:
{{cquote|The design of Arrow 3 promises to be an extremely capable system, more advanced than what we have ever attempted in the U.S. with our programs. [...] This has to do with the seekers that have greater flexibility and other aspects, such as propulsion systems - it will be an extremely capable system.<ref name="dua3" />}}
The new component will also require the integration of longer range detection, tracking and discrimination capability, beyond what the "Green Pine" and "Super Green Pine" radars employed with the Arrow 2 are providing. Among the advanced sensors considered for Israel's future multi-tier system, are airborne [[Electro-optics|electro-optical]] sensors deployed on high flying [[unmanned aerial vehicle]]s and future enhanced "Green Pine" radars, as well as the AN/TPY-2 radar already deployed in Israel, and operated by U.S. forces.<ref name=dua3/>

Israel Aerospace Industries announced in June 2009, that the Arrow 3 patented<ref name=pata3>{{citation | inventor1-last = Hasson | inventor1-first = Joseph | inventor2-last = Goldner | inventor2-first = Galia | title = Exo Atmospheric Intercepting System and Method | issue-date = 2006-01-12 | patent-number = 2006003660 | country-code = WO }}</ref> exoatmospheric interception method includes a two stage interceptor, like the Arrow 2, but purely based on hit-to-kill technology.<ref name="iaia3" /> IAI also displayed a full-sized model of the Arrow 3 at the June 2009 [[Paris Air Show]].<ref name=a3janes>{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/news/defence/systems/jmr/jmr090709_1_n.shtml |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |title=IAI exhibits full-size Arrow 3 at Paris |author=Doug Richardson |date=2009-07-09 |accessdate=2009-08-19}} See [http://i43.photobucket.com/albums/e381/frenchxavier/Bourget%2009/bourget093.jpg Arrow 2] and [http://i43.photobucket.com/albums/e381/frenchxavier/Bourget%2009/bourget094.jpg Arrow 3]. Retrieved 2009-09-23.</ref> Arrow 3 should be able to intercept ballistic missiles, including [[intermediate-range ballistic missile]]s,<ref name="armytec" /> at altitudes of over {{km to mi|100|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}},<ref name="yneta3">{{cite web |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3579000,00.html |publisher=[[Ynetnews]] |title=US to help Israel develop Arrow-3 |author=[[Ron Ben-Yishai]] |date=2008-07-08 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> and in greater ranges.<ref name="CRS2009"/> It is slightly smaller than the Arrow 2,<ref name="swa3">{{cite web |url=http://www.spacewar.com/reports/IAI_working_on_Arrow-3_anti-missile_999.html |publisher=Spacewar.com |title=IAI working on Arrow-3 anti-missile |date=2009-07-10 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> faster,<ref name="CRS2009" /> and may have a reduced 30-year life-cycle cost.<ref name=a3janes/> Reportedly it will only cost $1.5<U+2013>$2 million per unit,<ref name="yneta3"/> while program cost is estimated at some $700<U+2013>$800 million over three years.<ref name="a3-80" /> It is expected to be operational by 2012.<ref name="CRS2009"/> Lieutenant General O'Reilly, however, expressed concern about the schedule proposed by the Israelis.<ref name=dua3/> Reportedly, the U.S. will provide the full funding for the development and production of the Arrow 3.<ref name="fund">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1242212426298&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=US to fully fund Arrow 3 missile system |author=Yaakov Katz |date=2009-05-20 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref>

==Specifications==
[[File:Arrow missile interceptor cropped.jpg|upright=0.54|thumb|alt=Arrow 2 at the Paris Air Show. |Arrow 2 at the Paris Air Show.]]
The Arrow system was exclusively designed to intercept medium- and short-range ballistic missiles, with an eye on the advanced missile programs of [[Iran]] and [[Saddam Hussein]]'s [[Iraq]]. It is not intended to intercept either [[military aircraft]] or [[Rocket artillery|artillery rockets]], the second of which are relatively small and short ranged. In contrast to both [[Terminal High Altitude Area Defense|THAAD]], [[RIM-161 Standard Missile 3]] (exoatmospheric), and [[MIM-104 Patriot#PAC-3|MIM-104 Patriot PAC-3]] (low altitude), the Arrow intercepts its targets in the high [[stratosphere]], high enough so that any nuclear, chemical, or biological weapons do not scatter over Israel.<ref name=mstrt /> The developers' intention was to perform the destruction sequence away from populated locations.<ref name=iafs>{{cite web | publisher = [[Israeli Air Force]] | title= Israel Aircraft Industries 'Arrow' ('Hetz') - Systems | url = http://www.iaf.org.il/Templates/Aircraft/Aircraft.IN.aspx?lang=EN&lobbyID=69&folderID=87&docfolderID=907&docID=18137&currentPageNumber=6 | accessdate=2009-08-24}}</ref> According to Dr. [[Uzi Rubin]], the missile was tested to determine whether chemical warfare agents would reach the ground should such a [[warhead]] be intercepted. The conclusion was that nothing would reach the ground if the warhead is destroyed above the [[jet stream]], which flows from west to east and would therefore blow any chemical residue back to its point of origin.<ref group=n>Most likely - Syria.</ref><ref name="uzi">{{cite web |url=http://www.jcpa.org/jl/vp493.htm |publisher=[[Jerusalem Center for Public Affairs]] |author=Dr. [[Uzi Rubin]] |title= Beyond Iraq: Missile Proliferation in the Middle East |date=2003-03-02 |accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> Nevertheless, Arrow is also capable of low altitude interception, as well as multi<U+2014> tactical ballistic missiles interception.<ref name="iaibr"/> 

The two-stage missile is equipped with [[solid propellant]] [[Booster (rocketry)|booster]] and sustainer rocket motors.<ref name=armytec/> The missile uses an initial burn to carry out a vertical hot launch from the container and a secondary burn to sustain the missile's trajectory towards the target at a maximum speed of [[Mach number|Mach]] 9, or {{convert|2.5|km/s|1|lk=on|sp=us|abbr=on}}.<ref name=armytec/> [[Thrust vectoring|Thrust vector control]] is used in the boost and sustainer phases of flight.<ref name=armytec/> At the ignition of the second stage sustainer motor, the first stage assembly separates.<ref name=armytec/> The Arrow missile is launched before the threat missile's trajectory and intercept point are accurately known.<ref name=armytec/> As more trajectory data becomes available, the optimum intercept point is more precisely defined, towards which the missiles is then guided.<ref name=armytec/> The {{kg to lb|500|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} [[kill vehicle]] section of the missile, containing the warhead, fusing and the terminal seeker, is equipped with four moving delta aerodynamic control [[fin]]s to give low altitude interception capability.<ref name=nti2/> The dual mode missile seeker has a passive infrared seeker for the acquisition and tracking of tactical ballistic missiles and an active radar seeker used to home on air breathing targets at low altitudes.<ref name=armytec/> The [[infrared seeker]] is an [[indium antimonide]] [[focal plane]] array.<ref name=armytec/> The kill vehicle is designed to achieve a hit-to-kill interception, but if this is not achieved, the [[proximity fuze]] will direct the warhead fragments at the target shortly before reaching the closest point to the target.<ref name=nti2/> The high explosive directed blast fragmentation warhead is capable of destroying a target within a {{m to ft|50|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} radius.<ref name=armytec/>

According to [[Dov Raviv]], a senior developer dubbed "the father of the Arrow anti-ballistic missile",<ref group=n>As is Dr. [[Uzi Rubin]]. See: [http://www.jinsa.org/node/596 Dr. Uzi Rubin, "father" of Israel's Arrow Ballistic Missile Defense System, speaking at Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs Conference].</ref><ref name="father">{{cite web |url=http://archive.globes.co.il/searchgl/Father%20of%20the%20%EF%BF%BDArrow%EF%BF%BD%20missile%20Dov%20Raviv%20believes%20he_s_hd_1L3auD30oN34mC30nDp4vDJCkQ7HjR000.html |publisher=[[Globes]] |title=Father of the <U+2018>Arrow<U+2019> missile Dov Raviv believes he has the answer to Hizbullah<U+2019>s Katushyas. |author=Amnon Barzilai |accessdate=2009-08-23 |date=2007-11-01}}</ref><ref name="father2">{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?cid=1134309630444&pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FPrinter |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=Storm clouds gathering |author=Erik Schechter |accessdate=2009-08-23 |date=2005-12-22}}</ref> a single Arrow interceptor has a 90% probability of destroying a target missile at the highest altitude possible.<ref name="inss" /><ref name="stav">{{cite book| last = Stav| first = Arieh| title =The threat of ballistic missiles in the Middle East: active defense and countermeasures | pages= 38, 40 | publisher = [[Sussex Academic Press]]| year = 2004| isbn = 1845190017 | url = http://books.google.co.il/books?id=ldxHtsdiGG4C |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref><ref name="dov"/> In case of failure two more interceptors can be launched towards the target at short time intervals.<ref name="inss" /><ref name=mstrt /><ref name="stav" /> If the first of these destroys the target, the second can be directed to another target.<ref name="dov">{{cite web |url=http://www.elec.co.il/Articles/Item.asp?CategoryID=227&ArticleID=3385&VolumeID=15 |publisher=[http://www.elec.co.il/GeneralArticlesEng/Item.asp?CategoryID=244&ArticleID=5 ELECTRONICA] | trans_title =The nuclear threat on Israel - and the Arrow |title= <U+05D4><U+05D0><U+05D9><U+05D5><U+05DD> <U+05D4><U+05D2><U+05E8><U+05E2><U+05D9><U+05E0><U+05D9> <U+05E2><U+05DC> <U+05D9><U+05E9><U+05E8><U+05D0><U+05DC> - <U+05D5><U+05D4><U+05D7><U+05E5> |author=[[Dov Raviv]] - <U+05D3><U+05D5><U+05D1> <U+05E8><U+05D1><U+05D9><U+05D1> |language=[[Hebrew language|Hebrew]] |accessdate=2009-08-19 |date=2004-10-12}}</ref> Using this technique, three independent interception possibilities are provided which raise the interception probability from 90% to 99.9%, thus satisfying the leakage rate requirement.<ref name="stav" /><ref name="dov" /> The Arrow also has the capability to simultaneously intercept a salvo of more than five incoming missiles, with the target missiles arriving within a 30-second span.<ref name="father2"/> Such capability is currently possessed only by the United States and [[Russia]].<ref name="father2"/> According to Raviv, the Arrow can discriminate between a warhead and a [[decoy]].<ref name="father2"/>

Each battery is equipped with typically four to eight launch trailers, its manning requires about 100 personnel.<ref>{{cite book| last = Cordesman | first = Anthony H. |authorlink=Anthony Cordesman | title =Strategic threats and national missile defenses: defending the U.S. homeland |page=359 | publisher = [[Center for Strategic and International Studies]] |location= [[Washington, D.C.]] | year = 2002| isbn = 0275974251 | url = http://books.google.co.il/books?id=VsylMAAB2poC |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref> Each [[Trailer (vehicle)|trailer]]-mounted erector-launcher weighs {{convert|35|t|lb}}<ref name="Egozi2" /> when loaded with six launch tubes with ready-to-fire missiles.<ref name=armytec/> After firing the launchers can be reloaded in an hour.<ref name=armytec/>

