====Green Pine====
Elta, a [[subsidiary]] of IAI, was awarded the contract to develop and manufacture the EL/M-2080 "Green Pine" ({{lang-he|<U+05D0><U+05D5><U+05E8><U+05DF> <U+05D9><U+05E8><U+05D5><U+05E7>}}, {{IPA-he|o<U+0281>en ya<U+0281>ok|pron}}) radar in 1992.<ref name="video2">{{cite web |url=http://www.iai.co.il/sip_storage/files/9/32419.wmv |format=WMV |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |author=Israel Missile Defense Organization and United States Ballistic Missile Defense Organization |title=Green Pine}} See [[Mirror (computing)|mirror]]: {{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JNe2q4PPNkM |publisher=[[YouTube]] |title=Green Pine |date=2009-02-16 |accessdate=2009-10-01}}</ref> The "Green Pine" was developed from the Elta "Music" [[phased array]] radar,<ref name=armytec/> presented in November 1994,<ref name="video2" /> rolled out in 1995,<ref name="uzi" /> and turned operational in November 1998.<ref name="gphis">{{cite web |url=http://www.wisconsinproject.org/countries/israel/Israel-milestones2005.html |publisher=[[Wisconsin Project on Nuclear Arms Control]] |title=Israel Missile Milestones - 1953-2005 |date=2005 |accessdate=2009-09-08}}</ref> In 2000 it was revealed that the "Green Pine" detected the launch of a Syrian "Scud-D" missile from its base outside [[Aleppo]] in northern Syria, and tracked its full trajectory until its impact point, some {{km to mi|700|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} in the southern desert.<ref name="syria1">{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/2005/12/syrian-ambitions-to-develop-strategic.html|publisher=[http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] |title=Syrian Ambitions to develop a Strategic Missile Potential |date=2005-12-05 |accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> The "Green Pine" reportedly detected and tracked similar launches of Syrian "Scuds" also in 2005<ref name="syria2">{{cite web |url=http://www.missilethreat.com/archives/id.1947/detail.asp |publisher= [[Claremont Institute]] MissileThreat.com |http://missilethreat.com/missiledefensesystems/id.10/system_detail.asp |title=Syria Tests Three Scud Missiles |date=2005-06-03 |accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref> and in 2008.<ref name="syria3">{{cite web |url=http://www.haaretz.com/hasen/spages/1012826.html |author=Yuval Azoulay |publisher= [[Haaretz]] |title=Report: Syria test fires series of long-range missiles |date=2008-08-18 |accessdate=2009-09-10}}</ref>

The "Green Pine" is an [[Active Electronically Scanned Array]] (AESA) solid state radar operating at [[L band]] in the range 500 [[MHz]] to 1,000&nbsp;MHz,<ref name=armytec/> or 1,000&nbsp;MHz to 2,000&nbsp;MHz.<ref name="gpj">{{cite web |url=http://www.janes.com/articles/Janes-Radar-and-Electronic-Warfare-Systems/EL-M2080-Green-Pine-Israel.html |publisher=[[Jane's Information Group]] |title=EL/M-2080 'Green Pine' (Israel), Battlefield, missile control and ground surveillance radar systems |date=2009-01-03 |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref> It operates in search, detection, tracking, and missile guidance modes simultaneously.<ref name=armytec/> It is capable of detecting targets at ranges of up to about {{km to mi|500|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-2|wiki=no}} and is able to track targets at speeds over {{convert|3000|m/s|-3|lk=on|sp=us|abbr=on}}. The radar illuminates the target and guides the Arrow missile to within {{m to ft|4|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}} of the target.<ref name=armytec/> The [[effective radiated power]] of the "Green Pine" also makes it a possible candidate for conversion into a [[directed-energy weapon]].<ref name="dew">{{cite web |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_generic.jsp?channel=awst&id=news/12195p3.xml&headline=Israel%20Tests%20Improved%20Arrow%20Interceptor |publisher=[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]] |title=Israel Tests Improved Arrow Interceptor|date=2005-12-17 |author=David A. Fulghum |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> 

{{external media|align = right|width = 190px |image1 = [http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/he/4/49/EL-M-2080_Green_Pine.jpg "Green Pine" radar]|image2 = [http://www.iai-global.com/sip_storage/files/8/36878.gif "Super Green Pine" radar]}}
The radar system includes a {{m to ft|9|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}} wide by {{m to ft|3|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=0|wiki=no}} high<ref name="gpj" /> trailer-mounted rotatable [[Smart antenna|antenna array]], a [[power generator]], a cooling system and a radar control center.<ref name=armytec/> The radar comprises 2,000 transmit-receive modules and weighs {{convert|60|t|lb|lk=in}}.<ref name="Egozi2" /> Its deployment at a new operational site takes "less than 24 hours".<ref name="video2"/> 

An advanced version of the radar, called "Super Green Pine",<ref name="iaia3">{{cite web |url=http://www.iai-global.com/32981-39666-en/default.aspx?PageNum=2 |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |title=IAI Develops Arrow 3 Interceptor in Response to Longer Range Threats |accessdate=2009-06-10 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> "Green Pine" Block-B,<ref name="sk3" /> or "Great Pine" ({{lang-he|<U+05D0><U+05D5><U+05E8><U+05DF> <U+05D0><U+05D3><U+05D9><U+05E8>}}, {{IPA-he|o<U+0281>en adi<U+0281>|pron}}), is to take the place of the original "Green Pine. As of 2008 both versions were active.<ref name="syria3" /> The "Super Green Pine" is believed to produce double the power output,<ref name="dew" /> extending detection range to about {{convert|800|-|900|km|mi|abbr=on}}.<ref name="sk3" /><ref name="sk">{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4001378 |publisher=[[Defense News]]|author=Jung Sung-ki |title=S. Korea Boosts Missile Defenses |date=2009-03-23 |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref><ref name="Egozi3">{{cite web |url=http://www.flightglobal.com/articles/2009/09/23/332642/south-korea-picks-israeli-radar-for-fa-50-fighter.html |publisher=[[Flightglobal.com]] |title=South Korea picks Israeli radar for F/A-50 fighter |author=Arie Egozi |date=2003-09-23 |accessdate=2009-09-24}}</ref>

The [[Swordfish Long Range Tracking Radar]] of the [[India]]n [[Defence Research and Development Organisation]] is also an acknowledged derivative of the original "Green Pine".<ref name="swordfish">{{cite web |url=http://www.domain-b.com/aero/mil_avi/miss_muni/20090306_successful_missile.html |publisher= [http://www.domain-b.com/about_us/index.html domain-b.com] |title=India tests 'Swordfish' radar with successful missile defence test |date=2009-03-06 |accessdate=2009-09-22}}</ref>

====Golden Citron====
The "Golden Citron" ({{lang-he|<U+05D0><U+05EA><U+05E8><U+05D5><U+05D2> <U+05D6><U+05D4><U+05D1>}}, {{IPA-he|et<U+0281>og zahav|pron}}) truck-mounted [[net-centric]] [[open systems architecture]]<ref name="iaibr"/> Battle Management Command, Control, Communication & Intelligence Center<ref name=tests/> can control up to 14 intercepts simultaneously.<ref name=armytec/> As of 2007 it was one of the world's most advanced net-centric systems.<ref name=dua2>{{cite web |url=http://defense-update.com/features/du-2-06/ILmissiledefense-3.htm |publisher=[http://www.defense-update.com/about.htm Defense Update] |title=Israel's Strategic Defense Programs: Arrow's Spiral Evolution|accessdate=2009-08-19 |date=2007-03-01}}</ref> The system provides fully automatic as well as [[Human-in-the-Loop]] options at every stage<ref name="tadiran"/> of battle operation management.<ref name="iaibr">{{cite web |url=http://www.iai.co.il/sip_storage/files/6/34766.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |title=Arrow brochure |accessdate=2009-08-19}}</ref> It is also capable of interoperability with other theater missile defense systems and [[C4ISTAR|C<sup>3</sup>I]] systems.<ref name="tadiran">{{cite web |url=http://www.tadsys.com/images/Tmd.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Tadiran Telecom]] |title=Theater missile defense systems and programs brochure |accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref> Notably [[Link 16]], [[TADIL-J]], communications were being altered to allow interoperability with Patriot fire control units. Assigned targets can be handed over to the Patriot's [[MIM-104 Patriot#The AN/MPQ-53 and AN/MPQ-65 Radar Set|AN/MPQ-53]] fire control radar. Tests carried out by the U.S and Israel have successfully linked the Arrow with both U.S and Israeli versions of the Patriot.<ref name=armytec/> 

The "Citron Tree" has three banks of operator consoles laid out in a U shape. In the center sits the [[Officer (armed forces)|officer]] in command who oversees the engagement, but also has links to the other parts of the battery as well as to IAF [[headquarters]]. On the commander's right sits the engagement officer, who ensures that targets are assigned to other engagement officers sitting on the right-hand leg of the U. Each is assigned a geographical area to defend and two of the officers are more senior as they have an overview of Patriot batteries. To the left of the commander is the resource officer, who monitors the status and readiness of the missiles. On the left of the U sits the sky picture officer, who is in contact with the [[Home Front Command]] and uses the center's ability to predict impact point to alert the [[Civil defense in Israel|civil authorities]]. Also at these consoles are an [[Intelligence (information gathering)|intelligence]] officer and an [[After Action Review|after-action]] / [[Debriefing|debrief]] officer, who uses recordings as it is impossible to absorb all the information during engagements.<ref name="Egozi2"/>  All in all, the "Golden Citron" is manned by 7<U+2013>10 operators.<ref name=Bar-Joseph />

====Brown Hazelnut====
The "Brown Hazelnut" ({{lang-he|<U+05D0><U+05D2><U+05D5><U+05D6> <U+05D7><U+05D5><U+05DD>}}, {{IPA-he|egoz xum|pron}}) launch control center is located at the launch site,<ref name="iaibr"/> up to {{km to mi|300|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} from the "Golden Citron" fire control center.<ref name=armytec/> It employes [[microwave]] and [[radio]] data and voice communications links to the "Green Pine" and "Golden Citron". The launch method is a vertical hot launch from a sealed canister,<ref name=armytec/><ref name="iaibr"/> providing all-[[azimuth]] coverage.<ref name="iaibr"/> "Brown Hazelnut" also has missile maintenance and diagnostic capabilities.<ref name="iaibr"/>

==Production==
[[File:Arrow coverage.png|thumb|upright=1.2|alt=Coverage of Israel provided by two Arrow 2 batteries, derived from their published locations (Palmachim, Ein Shemer) and range (90-100 km). |Coverage of Israel provided by two Arrow 2 batteries, derived from their published locations (Palmachim, Ein Shemer) and range (90-100 km).]]
Israel initially produced the Arrow system domestically,<ref group=n>Except for Lockheed Martin's active radar seeker.</ref> but on February 11, 2003 IAI and Boeing signed an agreement, valued at over $25 million for fiscal years 2003<U+2013>2004,<ref name=boeing/> to establish production facilities for the manufacture of components for the Arrow missile in the United States. In March 2004, IAI awarded a $78 million production contract to Boeing; the total contract value could exceed $225 million through second quarter 2008.<ref name=boeing/> As a result of successful implementation of this contract Boeing is responsible for production of about 35%<ref name=boeing>{{cite web |url=http://www.boeing.com/defense-space/space/arrow/docs/Arrow_overview.pdf |format=PDF|publisher=[[Boeing]] |title=Arrow II brochure |accessdate=2009-08-19 |date=2008-03}}</ref><U+2013>50% of Arrow missile components, including the electronics section, booster motor case and missile canister,<ref name=armytec/><ref name=boeing/> at its [[Huntsville, Alabama]] facilities.<ref name=Huntsville>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4087827 |publisher=[[Defense News]]|title=Boeing Moving Missile Unit to Alabama |author=Antonie Boessenkool |date=2009-05-13 |accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref> IAI, the prime contractor of the Arrow system, is responsible for integration and the final assembly of the Arrow missile in Israel.<ref name=tests/> Boeing also coordinates the production of Arrow missile components manufactured by more than 150 American companies.<ref name=armytec/> Boeing delivered its first Arrow 2 interceptor to Israel in 2005.<ref name=mstrt/><ref name=boeing/> Co-produced interceptors has been tested since February 12, 2007.<ref name="mda2">{{cite web |url=http://www.mda.mil/mdalink/pdf/07fyi0096.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Missile Defense Agency]] |title=News release: February 12, 2007|date=2007-02-12 |accessdate=2009-09-01}}</ref>

Other major contractors are:
* [[Elta]] - produces the "Green Pine" / "Super Green Pine" radar;<ref name="elta"/>
* [[Tadiran Telecom]] - produces the "Golden Citron" [[C4ISTAR|C<sup>3</sup>I]] Center;<ref name="tadiran"/>
* [[Rafael Advanced Defense Systems]] - produces the sustainer motor and the warhead;<ref name=armytec/>
* [[Israel Military Industries]] - produces the booster motor;<ref name=armytec/>
* [[Alliant Techsystems]] - produces the motor cases and the first stage [[nozzle]];<ref name=armytec/>
* [[Lockheed Martin]] - produces the active radar seeker;<ref name="mda3">{{cite web |url=http://www.mda.mil/mdalink/html/arrwast5.html |publisher=[[Missile Defense Agency]] |title=U.S. Army Program Executive Office Air and Missile Defense' Public Affairs Office, Memorandum for Correspondents |date=2000-09-14 |accessdate=2009-09-01}}</ref>
* [[Raytheon]] - produces the infrared seeker;<ref name=armytec/>
* [[Ceradyne]] - produces the [[ceramic]] [[radome]].<ref name="cera">{{cite web |url=http://www.ceradyne.com/uploads/Radome%20White%20Paper%20PDF.pdf |format=PDF |publisher=[[Ceradyne]] |title=Ceramic Radomes for Tactical Missile Systems |accessdate=2009-09-21}}</ref>

==Deployment==
The first operational Arrow battery was deployed in March 2000 in [[Palmachim Airbase]], near the city of [[Rishon LeZion]], south of the [[Tel Aviv]] [[metropolitan area]]. It was declared operational in October 2000, and reached its full capacity in March 2001.<ref name="video">{{cite web |url=http://www.iai.co.il/sip_storage/files/6/34806.wmv |format=WMV |publisher=[[Israel Aerospace Industries]] |author=Israel Missile Defense Organization and United States Ballistic Missile Defense Organization |title=Arrow missile}} See [[Mirror (computing)|mirror]]: {{cite web |url=http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=94eF5z55ydg  |publisher=[[YouTube]] |title=Arrow missile |date=2008-08-29 |accessdate=2009-08-25}}</ref> Deployment of the second battery at [[Ein Shemer]],<ref name=mstrt/> near the city of [[Hadera]], [[Haifa District]], northern Israel, was delayed by strong opposition from local residents who feared its radar would be hazardous to their health.<ref name=global/> The situation was eventually resolved and Israel's second battery completed its deployment, turned operational and linked up with first battery in October 2002. In 2007, however, the IDF has reportedly decided to modify its missile defense doctrine and in order to counter possible Syrian and Iranian missile [[Barrage (artillery)|barrages]] and has modified its deployment of the Arrow in northern Israel.<ref name=change>{{cite web |url=http://www.jpost.com/servlet/Satellite?pagename=JPost%2FJPArticle%2FShowFull&cid=1187779147684 |publisher=[[The Jerusalem Post]] |title=IDF modifying Arrow deployment in the North |author=Yaakov Katz |date=2007-08-23 |accessdate=2009-08-21}}</ref>

Israel had originally planned to deploy two Arrow 2 batteries but has since sought and won promises of funding for a third battery.<ref name=global/> Some reports state that a third battery is already deployed,<ref name="inss" /> or in development in the south,<ref name=mstrt/> while others claim that a decision on deployment of a third battery has not yet been made, although it is under discussion for service entry in 2012.<ref name=armytec/> Unconfirmed reports suggest that the first battery is actually in the southern [[Negev]] desert, at the [[Negev Nuclear Research Center]] near the town of [[Dimona]].<ref name=global/> Another report states that Israel plans to deploy not one, but two additional Arrow 2 batteries to defend the country's southern region, also covering sensitive sites such as the Negev Nuclear Research Center.<ref name="a3-80"/> The IDF plans to procure 50<ref name=sipri /><U+2013>100 interceptors for each battery.<ref name=mstrt/> As of 1998, a battery was estimated to cost about $170 million.<ref name=global/><ref name="batcost">{{cite web |url=http://www.wisconsinproject.org/countries/israel/missile2000.htm |publisher=[[Wisconsin Project on Nuclear Arms Control]] |title=Israel Missile Update - 2000 |date=2000 |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref><ref group=n>Without the cost of the missiles.</ref>

===Export===
Apart from Israel no country has yet to purchase a full Arrow system, although [[India]] had acquired and deployed two "Green Pine" radars around July 2002 and another one in August 2005.<ref name="india">{{cite web |url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/world/india/bmd.htm |author = [[John E. Pike]] |publisher=[[GlobalSecurity.org]] |title=India: Ballistic Missile Defense |accessdate=2009-08-26}}</ref> The [[Indian government]] has sought to purchase the Arrow system since 1999,<ref name=dtic /> however in early 2002 the U.S. vetoed Israel's request to sell the Arrow 2 missiles to India,<ref name=global/><ref name="india" /> exercising its right as a major funding contributor.<ref>{{cite book| last = Assamann| first = Lars| title =Theater Missile Defense (TMD) in East Asia: Implications for Beijing and Tokyo | publisher = [[Transaction Publishers]]| year = 2007| isbn = 9783825802233 | page=205 |url = http://books.google.co.il/books?id=jyM2hhUlfD8C |accessdate=2009-09-12}}</ref> U.S. officials argued that the sale would violate the [[Missile Technology Control Regime]] (MTCR).<ref name=global/> Although the Arrow 2 could possibly achieve a range of {{km to mi|300|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}}, it is designed for intercepts at shorter ranges, and it is unclear whether it could carry a {{kg to lb|500|sp=us|abbr=on|precision=-1|wiki=no}} payload to this range specified in the MTCR.<ref name=global/><ref name=nti2>{{cite web |url=http://nuclearthreatinitiative.org/d_newswire/issues/2002/7/10/8s.html |publisher=[[Nuclear Threat Initiative]] |title=Israel: Raytheon Fights Israeli Efforts to Market Arrow |date=2002-07-10 |accessdate=2009-09-19}}</ref>

[[South Korea]] was also considering buying two "Green Pine" radars, which would become operational in 2012.<ref name="sk"/><ref name=sk2>{{cite web |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/09/205_39599.html |publisher=[[The Korea Times]]|author=Jung Sung-ki |title=Israeli Radar to Track N. Korean Missiles |date=2009-02-15 |accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref> Reportedly, South Korea has finally preferred two "Super Green Pine" radars at a cost of $83 million each over its counterpart - [[ThalesRaytheonSystems]]' M3R radars.<ref name="sk3">{{cite web |url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2009/09/113_52006.html |publisher=[[The Korea Times]]|author=Jung Sung-ki |title=Israeli Radar Chosen for Missile Defense |date=2009-09-17 |accessdate=2009-09-17}}</ref><ref name="sk" /> [[Turkey]] also planned to buy anti-missile air defense systems worth more than $1 billion. The Arrow was considered a potential contender,<ref name=turkey>{{cite web |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3927941 |publisher=[[Defense News]] |title=Turk-Israeli Deals Threatened by Gaza |author=Umit Enginsoy and Burak Ege Bekdil |date=2009-02-02 |accessdate=2009-08-22}}</ref> however Turkey has apparently chosen the Patriot PAC-3.<ref name=turkey2>{{cite web |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/latestCrisis/idUSLH183802 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |title=Turkey: any Patriot missile buy not due to threat |author=Paul de Bendern |date=2009-09-17 |accessdate=2009-09-20}}</ref>

In the late 1990s officials of [[Jordan]] have expressed concern that any conflagration between Israel and Iraq or Iran would impact its territory. The problem becomes more difficult for Jordan when the warheads are not conventional. Therefore [[Benjamin Netanyahu]], during his first term of office as Prime Minister of Israel, reportedly offered Jordan "a defensive umbrella of Arrow 2". Without allowing Israel to forward deploy the Arrow launchers close to the Iraqi border, the other option is for Israel to sell Jordan the Arrow system. This is most likely what Prime Minister Netanyahu meant above. In May 1999 Israel reportedly requested U.S. approval for selling Arrow batteries to Jordan, but apparently no such approval has been given yet.<ref name=dtic>{{cite web | author = [[Guermantes E. Lailari]] | title = Israel's National Missile Defense Strategy | format = PDF | publisher = [[Defense Technical Information Center]]  | date = 2001-04 | url = http://www.dtic.mil/cgi-bin/GetTRDoc?AD=ADA407050&Location=U2&doc=GetTRDoc.pdf | accessdate = 2009-09-22 }}</ref>  

In the past, the [[United Kingdom]], [[Japan]], and [[Singapore]] were mentioned as then potential foreign customers of the Arrow system.<ref name=global/><ref name=dtic /> [[Netherlands]] reportedly expressed interest in the "Golden Citron" [[C4ISTAR|C<sup>3</sup>I]] center in November 1999.<ref name=dtic />

For the United States, the Arrow has provided important technical and operational data.<ref name="jewish" /> It remains a key element in the Missile Defense Agency<U+2019>s plan for a layered missile defense architecture, and an example of a successful, affordable program. At the moment, however, the United States does not have any plans to procure and deploy the Arrow.<ref name=mstrt/> Nevertheless in September 2009 the Arrow system was mentioned by U.S. [[United States Secretary of Defense|Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]] and [[Vice Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff]] [[General (United States)|General]] [[James Cartwright]] among the alternative to the proposed [[US missile defense complex in Poland|U.S. missile defense assets in Europe]].<ref name="europe">{{cite web |url=http://www.defenselink.mil/transcripts/transcript.aspx?transcriptid=4479 |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] |title=DoD News Briefing with Secretary Gates and Gen. Cartwright from the Pentagon |accessdate=2009-09-18 |date=2009-09-17}}</ref><ref name="europe2">{{cite web |url=http://www.ynetnews.com/articles/0,7340,L-3778586,00.html |publisher=[[Ynetnews]] |author=[[Associated Press]] |title=US says forces to employ Israeli 'Arrow' in missile system |accessdate=2009-09-18 |date=2009-09-17}}</ref> Currently the Arrow system is being incorporated into U.S. anti-ballistic capability in [[Europe]], they said.<ref name="europe" />

